1. First and foremost, we believe that the preservation of Democracy is paramount.  Without a real functioning Democracy the people of America lose the ability to secure LIfe, Liberty, and the pursuit of Happiness.

2. We believe Government can be and should be a positive tool to improve the lives of average Americans, and we believe Americans have a right to insist that Government is effective and fair.

3. We believe in a robust defense of the State and other Environment.  We believe the threat of Climate change is real and warrants a serious response.

4. We believe that the economy needs to work for all Americans.  America pioneered smart industrial policy aimed at providing a building a prosperous middle class.  We can and should do it again.

5. We believe America has become excessively unequal, and that tax policy should tax large fortunes more and the middle class less, while doing everything possible to encourage entrepreneurs to build the growth engines of the future.

6. We believe the Government has an important role to play in stimulating research and development as the basis for future economic growth.
feedItems.title: Organizational Principles

feedItems.author: Hamilton
feedItems.content:
Hi.  I'm the creator of dWorld.  I'd like to explain the thinking behind this effort and why I believe it can help heal our politics.  

dWorld - the small 'd' is for democracy - is a social network built on privacy, organization, and AI.  There is no underlying algorithm trying to "stimulate engagement".  No one will sell any information about you to anyone.  Instead, we're about encouraging community and organization.   You will have the option to join one or more organizations through the app.  Your feed will be influenced by the organizations you join.  Of course you can use the platform to communicate with anyone you want.  

Our initial objective as a community is to help preserve Democracy by pushing back against the Trump Administration's authoritarian initiatives.  

We believe that Democracy should deliver, and our chosen strategy is to empower individuals to join and build organizations.  More than that, we believe organizations, including the Government and the Democratic Party, need to deliver tangible results rather than just rhetoric.   That's why this app is built around an AI, which can help you understand the implications of policies and strategies on You and your family.  It can also help you use the app.   Feel free to ask it anything.   The AI's job is to help explain how you can be more successful and become a more engaged, effective citizen. 

The model that sustains all this is simple: instead of selling your information we ask for $5/month.   We will put those funds to work preserving your privacy, enhancing your community, and hopefully delivering information that is worth much more.   But we won't turn anyone away.  

Garrett
feedItems.title: What dWorld is all About

feedItems.author: Hamilton
feedItems.content:
The first amazing thing about this experiment is that it is possible at all - I've developed all this (and the servers that support it) without writing a line of code.  

The idea is that, as my organization theory, professor said, "an organization is a mobilized bias".   In a sense, a social network is also an organized bias, but the bias is towards engagement and is implemented by an algorithm. My idea is to build something like a social network, but around organizations. The organizations would curate the Feed in furtherance of the objectives of the organization. The AI is there to help the user understand things they encounter in the Feed, and the world in general.

I'd love to give you a tour when you have a chance. I leave for Ukraine on 6/5.   Do you have any time between now and then?

GG

<<<PLOT_LOGIC_SCRIPT>>>
PRINT "Welcome back! Let's check if your contacts are registered to vote."
ASK "Do you have your contacts list ready?" = ready
IF (ready = YES) THEN PRINT "Wonderful! I'll guide you through the process." ELSE PRINT "No problem. Please gather your contacts list and try again when ready."
PRESENT: PRESENTATION "Voter Registration Check Guide"
WHEN @isPresentationMode = FALSE THEN PRINT "Presentation completed! Now let's check your voter registration status."
ASK "Shall I proceed?" = proceed
IF (proceed = YES) THEN PRINT "Wonderful! This should take a few minutes"

feedItems.author: Jefferson
feedItems.content:
Lots of new features in this release:

1. Easy creation of YouTube and Podcast FeedItems
2. FeedItems relevant to the 2026 Mid Terms can be flagged. Choose the ‘2026 Mid-Term’ topic in EditView when creating a FeedItem
3. INCLUDE command in PlotLogic works well.  Try typing ‘how do I use the include command?’
4. Thumbs up/down icon for ranking FeedItems
5. ‘Onboard:’ enhanced.  Try typing ‘onboard:’
6. New ‘help: <help topics>’ command
7. Lots of new ‘Please …’ commands, including ‘Please hide <FeedItem Type>’
8. Claude is the new AI default.  You can change it with the command ‘AiMode: ChangeAgent’ or ‘AiMode: OpenAI’
9. There is now a REPLY icon for Direct Messages
10. Scripting has become more powerful with WHEN, AIASK, and SUBMIT commands.  Try typing ‘I’m really pissed about Trump.  What can I do that matters?’
11. Double-clicking on any FeedItem takes you to Full Screen Mode  and puts that Item at the top of the scrolling list.

And more…

feedItems.author: Jefferson
feedItems.content:
If your goal is to reduce the power of those who cheer political violence, how do you strategically respond to acts of political violence? This is unfortunately a real-life strategic question we’ve been wrestling with all year. So I have some thoughts, and Indivisible has some actions.

Political violence hurts democracy. Period. Minutes after the news broke that Charlie Kirk had been shot, we had a group leader call with a few hundred Indivisible leaders across the country. On that call and in a statement, we condemned this horrifying attack, expressed our deepest condolences to Kirk’s wife and two young children, and reasserted our commitment to peaceful, people-powered organizing.

This is more or less what we did after Minnesota House Speaker Melissa Hortman and her husband were assassinated in June; and after the firebombing of Governor Shapiro's residence in April; and after the shooting of Trump in July of last year; and after the attempted murder of Nancy Pelosi’s husband in 2022; and after the bloody insurrection at the Capitol in 2021; and after the kidnapping plot against Governor Whitmer in 2020.

This is not an academic thing for us. Like judges and other public figures, Indivisible broadly, and Leah and myself specifically, have been threatened by right-wingers all year. And we’ve heard similar stories from Indivisible leaders around the country.

So at Indivisible we’re very clear: political violence is a cancer on democracy. It doesn’t matter if you disagree politically -- and we strongly disagreed with Charlie Kirk on basically everything. But we’re clear that political violence in any form is an attack on the basic conditions that allow everyone to organize and voice their views.

There’s a clear line: Do you condemn all political violence, no matter the perpetrator or the target? In the Indivisible movement, we are people who will condemn, with our whole hearts, such violence no matter the target or the perpetrator. We know the path forward is nonviolent, peaceful organizing.

Moments like this call for moral and strategic clarity across the political spectrum. And one of the challenges in organizing for democracy in the current moment is that the president of the United States is not interested in reducing right-wing political violence. That’s not an editorial statement by me -- that’s a verifiable fact.

Trump shrugs at right-wing political violence. We know what Trump thinks about right-wing political violence because he tells us with his words and actions.

He jokes about the brutal assault of Paul Pelosi, or says that expressing concern for the murdered Minnesota politician would be a “waste of time.” Asked about right-wing political violence on Fox News, of all places, Trump said “I couldn’t care less” before concluding with an attack on Democrats, trans kids, and immigrants.

So what do we do about it? Shrugging at political violence is dangerous for democracy, but issuing statements and moving on is insufficient. In the face of this violence -- and the right-wing escalation -- we need to be intentional, principled, and courageous. We also need to understand the strategies for how large-scale, broad-based, peaceful, people-powered organizing best operates in this environment.

That organizing must be informed by best practices around how to identify, defuse, and prevent the spread of political violence. Indivisible is offering a training on that this Sunday, September 21, at 8pm ET / 5pm PT -- you can register here. And if you want to do the reading ahead of time, you can find the 123-page curriculum here!

Training is important, but the point of training is action. That training needs to inform large-scale acts of opposition to violence-backed authoritarianism, so we need your help to make No Kings on October 18 the biggest peaceful protest of the year. Please spread the word, register your local protest as soon as you can, and start RSVPing for the local events to help build momentum.

I know the threats are real and the opposition is shameless and unrepentant. The way we triumph is by demonstrating courage with our actions. By standing up in defense of democracy and in opposition to violence, we spread the courage for more to do so.

We get out of this together -- each of us doing our part. That’s how we win. And we will win.

In solidarity,
Ezra Levin
Co-Executive Director, Indivisible

feedItems.author: Jefferson
feedItems.content:
In June, we did what many claimed was impossible: peacefully mobilized millions of people to take to the streets and declare with one voice: America has No Kings. And it mattered. The world saw the power of the people. President Trump’s birthday parade was drowned out by protests in every state and across the globe. His attempt to turn June 14 into a coronation collapsed, and the story became the strength of a movement rising against his authoritarian power grabs.

Now, President Trump has doubled down. His administration is sending masked agents into our streets, terrorizing our communities. They are targeting immigrant families, profiling, arresting and detaining people without warrants. Threatening to overtake elections. Gutting healthcare, environmental protections, and education when families need them most. Rigging maps to silence voters. Ignoring mass shootings at our schools and in our communities. Driving up the cost of living while handing out massive giveaways to billionaire allies, as families struggle.

The president thinks his rule is absolute. But in America, we don’t have kings and we won’t back down against chaos, corruption, and cruelty.

Our peaceful movement is only getting bigger and bigger. “NO KINGS” is more than just a slogan; it is the foundation our nation was built upon. Born in the streets, shouted by millions, carried on posters and chants, it echoes from city blocks to rural town squares, uniting people across this country to fight dictatorship together.

Because this country does not belong to kings, dictators, or tyrants. It belongs to We the People - the people who care, who show up, and the ones who fight for dignity, a life we can afford, and real opportunity. No Thrones. No Crowns. No Kings.
